\section{Introduction}
Modern baseball analytics has shifted the focus from simple outcomes like hits and runs to the underlying physics of the ball-bat collision. This report utilizes Statcast pitch-by-pitch data from the 2024 season to investigate two primary pillars of pitching performance. First, we examine organizational effectiveness across the American League Central division to see if team-wide philosophies produce measurably different results. Second, we investigate the "Time Through the Order" (TTO) penalty to quantify the degradation of a pitcher's effectiveness as a game progresses. Our primary response variable is \textbf{xwOBA on contact}, which utilizes exit velocity and launch angle to isolate a pitcher's true talent from defensive variance.

\section{Section 1: One-Factor ANOVA — AL Central Pitching Staffs}

\subsection{Motivation and Experimental Design}
Organizational culture and coaching philosophies in the AL Central vary significantly. While the Detroit Tigers and Cleveland Guardians have prioritized high-efficiency rotations, the Chicago White Sox have faced historic struggles. To determine if these outcomes represent statistically significant differences in organizational efficacy rather than random noise, we conduct a one-factor ANOVA across five independent groups ($g=5$): CLE, CWS, DET, KC, and MIN.

Our null hypothesis ($H_0$) states that all five staffs allow an identical mean quality of contact:
\begin{equation}
    H_0: \mu_{CLE} = \mu_{CWS} = \mu_{DET} = \mu_{KC} = \mu_{MIN}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
    H_a: \exists (i, j) \text{ such that } \mu_i \neq \mu_j
\end{equation}

\subsection{Assumption Testing: Quantitative and Qualitative Rigor}

\subsubsection{Qualitative Independence and Sample Selection}
Independence is a core assumption of the ANOVA framework. Each at-bat is assigned to one pitcher's team. To prevent "cross-contamination" of the means, we filtered the dataset to exclude any "multi-team" pitchers who appeared for more than one AL Central club in 2024. This ensures the $n \approx 31,000$ total observations represent mutually exclusive sets.

\subsubsection{Normality: The Shapiro-Francia ($W_{SF}$) Metric}
With group sizes of $n \approx 6,200$, normality tests are hypersensitive to minor fluctuations due to the Glivenko-Cantelli theorem. We formally test normality using the Shapiro-Francia statistic, which measures the correlation between ordered sample data ($X_{(k)}$) and expected normal quantiles ($a_k$):
\begin{equation}
    W_{SF} = \frac{(\sum a_k X_{(k)})^2}{\sum (X_k - \bar{X})^2}
\end{equation}
All groups returned $p = 0.000$, formally rejecting normality. However, the QQ-plots (Figure 1) reveal a right-skew typical of xwOBA data, where weak contact (pop-ups/dribblers) creates a mass near zero. We proceed with the ANOVA but acknowledge this violation motivates the Section 2.5 non-parametric follow-up.

