\subsubsection{Homoscedasticity: Bartlett’s Test}
A critical requirement for the standard $F$-test is equal group variances ($\sigma^2$). We test this using the Bartlett statistic ($B$):
\begin{equation}
    B = \frac{(n-g) \ln(\hat{s}_p^2) - \sum \nu_j \ln(s_j^2)}{1 + \frac{1}{3(g-1)} \left( \sum \frac{1}{\nu_j} - \frac{1}{n-g} \right)}
\end{equation}
The test yielded $B = 59,012.38$ ($p < 0.001$), providing overwhelming evidence that variances are unequal and mandating a heteroscedastic correction.

\subsection{Methodology: Welch’s Heteroscedastic ANOVA}
Because the homoscedasticity assumption failed, the standard ANOVA is invalid. We utilize Welch’s ANOVA, which uses Satterthwaite’s approximation to calculate a corrected denominator degrees of freedom ($\nu^*$):
\begin{equation}
    \nu^* = \frac{(\sum w_j)^2}{\sum (w_j^2 / \nu_j)}, \quad w_j = \frac{n_j}{s_j^2}
\end{equation}

