    \caption{MC Permutation Null Distribution for Section 1. The red line ($T_{obs}$) sits deep in the right tail, significantly exceeding the critical value at $\alpha=0.05$ (blue dashed line).}
    \label{fig:perm_sec1}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Statistical Power and Sensitivity}
To ensure the reliability of this result, we performed a Power Estimation under the alternative hypothesis ($H_a^*$), where the true group means match our observed sample.

\begin{equation}
    \text{Power} = P(\text{Reject } H_0 \mid H_a \text{ is true}) \approx 0.927
\end{equation}

With a 92.7\% power rating (Wald 95\% CI: 0.911, 0.943), we have extremely high confidence that the test is sensitive enough to detect these divisional differences. Because this result aligns with our Welch's $F$-test ($p = 0.0013$), we conclude that the organizational disparity in contact quality—specifically Detroit's superiority over Chicago—is a statistically significant.

\subsection{Results and Discussion of Impact}
Welch's ANOVA produced an observed $F^* = 4.493$ ($p = 0.00125$), leading us to reject $H_0$.
\\
\textbf{Consequences of Met Assumptions:} Detroit’s staff allowed significantly lower mean xwOBA ($\approx 0.297$) than Chicago ($\approx 0.322$). For a front office, this validates Detroit’s development program as a model for the division, justifying the market premium on their coaching staff.
\\
\textbf{Consequences of Unmet Assumptions:} If the independence assumption is violated—specifically if certain teams faced "easier" divisional schedules—our results may suffer from a Type I error, falsely attributing scheduling luck to organizational skill.

