\section{Section 2: Repeated-Measures ANOVA — The Time Through the Order Penalty}

\subsection{Motivation and Subject-Based Experimental Design}
Transitioning from organizational analysis to individual performance, we investigate the "Time Through the Order" (TTO) penalty. This phenomenon suggests a systemic degradation in a pitcher’s effectiveness as batters gain repeated visual familiarity with their repertoire within a single contest. We utilize a \textbf{Repeated-Measures ANOVA (RM-ANOVA)} on a sample of $n=311$ eligible pitchers from the 2024 season. 

By treating each pitcher as their own control, we utilize a within-subject design that effectively partitions out "subject-level" noise (individual talent baselines), allowing for a high-precision isolation of the TTO effect.

\begin{equation}
    H_0: \mu_{TTO1} = \mu_{TTO2} = \mu_{TTO3}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
    H_a: \exists (i, j) \text{ such that } \mu_i \neq \mu_j
\end{equation}

\subsection{Assumption Testing: Sphericity and Normality}

\subsubsection{Normality: Shapiro-Francia ($W_{SF}$) Assessment}
We formally assessed the normality of the mean xwOBA distributions for each TTO level using the Shapiro-Francia test. All levels returned $p = 0.000$, indicating a formal rejection. The departure was most severe at TTO 3 ($W_{SF} = 0.744$), which is likely driven by the increased volatility and smaller at-bat samples available as pitchers tire in later innings.

\begin{figure}[ht]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{qq_plots_rm_normality.png}
    \caption{Qualitative Normality Assessment: QQ-Plots for Pitcher Mean xwOBA by TTO. The heavy right-skew at TTO 3 is visually distinct, confirming increased performance volatility as the game progresses.}
    \label{fig:qq_sec2}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Quantitative Sphericity: Mauchly's Test and Epsilon Corrections}
RM-ANOVA requires \textbf{Sphericity}: the condition where the variances of the differences between all pairs of TTO levels are equal. We evaluate this using Mauchly’s $W$ and its associated $\chi^2$ approximations:
\begin{equation}
    W = \frac{\det(\hat{\Sigma})}{\hat{\sigma}^{2g}} = 0.260
\end{equation}
With $M_o = 416.72$ ($p < 0.001$), we find overwhelming evidence of a sphericity violation. To maintain a nominal Type I error rate, we apply the \textbf{Greenhouse-Geisser ($\epsilon_{GG}$)} correction to "shrink" the degrees of freedom:
\begin{equation}
    \nu_{MSM} = (g-1)\epsilon_{GG} \approx 1.37, \quad \nu_{MSE} = (n-1)(g-1)\epsilon_{GG} \approx 426.0
\end{equation}

\subsection{Non-Parametric Validation via Within-Subject Permutation}
Given the heavy normality violations ($p_{SF} = 0.000$), we validate the parametric results using a distribution-free \textbf{Within-Subject Permutation Test}. This method preserves the repeated-measures dependency by permuting TTO labels only within each pitcher’s row, effectively building an empirical null distribution that requires no assumption of normality.

Our custom test statistic, $T$, represents the range of the observed column means. Shuffling the labels 10,000 times produced an empirical $p = 0.0001$. This "Gold Standard" validation confirms the penalty is a statistically stable physical reality.

