The GG-corrected $F$-test ($F = 7.618, p = 0.0025$) reveals a significant monotonic increase in contact quality.

\subsection{Discussion of Impact and Consequences}
\textbf{Consequences of Met Assumptions:} The monotonic degradation ($0.317 \rightarrow 0.345$) statistically justifies the modern "opener" strategy and the tactical removal of starters before the third look at a lineup. The lack of overlap in bootstrap CIs between TTO 1 and TTO 3 confirms a practically meaningful performance cliff.
\\
\textbf{Consequences of Unmet Assumptions:} Ignoring the sphericity violation would lead to a severely inflated Type I error rate. Furthermore, the non-normality suggests the "penalty" may be non-uniform across the population; a subset of "collapsing" pitchers may be driving the mean, potentially leading managers to pull consistent, high-end outliers prematurely.

