\section{Section 3: Non-Parametric Evaluation of Pitching Volatility}

\subsection{Motivation and Custom Statistic Design}
To fulfill the requirement for a designed test statistic assessing a claim not associated with central tendency, we investigate the "Contact Volatility" of Tarik Skubal. While the previous sections established league-wide trends in mean performance, Section 3 examines the \textbf{stability} of a pitcher's mechanical output under high-leverage pressure. We hypothesize that the presence of base-runners ("Runners On") creates a high-stress environment that may increase the variance (volatility) of the contact allowed, even if the mean remains stable.

We define a custom metric, \textbf{Trajectory-Weighted Exit Velocity (TEV)}, which rewards optimal line-drive launch angles by centering the weight at $20^\circ$:
\begin{equation}
    TEV_i = \text{launch\_speed}_i \times \cos\left( (\text{launch\_angle}_i - 20^\circ) \frac{\pi}{180} \right)
\end{equation}

Our primary test statistic, $\tau_{vol}$, is designed to measure the absolute difference in TEV variances between leverage states:
\begin{equation}
    \tau_{vol} = s^2_{TEV}(\text{Runners On}) - s^2_{TEV}(\text{Bases Empty})
\end{equation}

\subsection{Computational Framework: Monte Carlo and Bootstrapping}
Because $\tau_{vol}$ is a non-standard variance-based metric, it lacks a known theoretical sampling distribution. We therefore employ a dual-computational approach to ensure the robustness of our conclusions:

\subsubsection{Monte Carlo Permutation Test}
To determine the significance of our observed $\tau_{vol}$, we conducted a permutation test with $nmc = 10,000$ iterations. Under the null hypothesis ($H_0$), "Leverage" carries no predictive power regarding contact volatility. By shuffling the leverage labels across Skubal's 553 contact at-bats, we constructed an empirical null distribution to calculate a two-tailed $p$-value.

\subsubsection{Bootstrap Confidence Intervals }
Following the methodology established in Lecture 09, we performed a bootstrap simulation with $nboot = 10,000$ resamples \textit{with replacement}. This allows us to estimate the precision of our volatility estimate and determine if the true difference in variance could realistically be zero.

