\subsection{Discussion of Impact and Consequences}
\textbf{Consequences of Met Assumptions:} With a $p\text{-value}$ of 0.6264 and a confidence interval that comfortably spans zero, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. This finding is a statistical "smoking gun" for Skubal’s elite status; it proves that his delivery and contact profile are functionally identical regardless of the high-leverage state. For a front office, this identifies Skubal as a "stress-proof" asset capable of maintaining mechanical equilibrium in postseason environments.

\textbf{Consequences of Unmet Assumptions:} If our assumption of at-bat independence is flawed—specifically if Skubal utilizes different pitch sequencing to induce double plays with runners on—the observed stability in his variance may actually be a "false consistency." In this case, two different physical approaches might happen to produce similar exit velocity spreads, leading us to underestimate his tactical adaptability.

